post_text:
Dear East Jordan Families:

Thank you very much for your patience during this very unusual time in education. Below are three communications that are being sent out to all our families today. When you take a look at this information, you will see a letter from Superintendent Stevenson, our plan for the beginning of the school year and some frequently asked questions. We will be requesting that all families complete a 2020-21 Registration form. This electronic form that will be sent to your email tomorrow. We will continue to provide our families with more information so be sure to check your email and our website at www.ejps.org for additional updates.

All mask invoices have been sent out! I did have a few no names with no email addresses. If you believe you filled in the pre-order form but did not receive an invoice, it is because of that. Let me know who you are and I will find your order and fill your name in. As of now, the masks should be in at the end of August. The easiest way for me to distribute them will be at the school open house on August 27th. There will be more opportunities for pickup, I just don’t know when because I don’t have a delivery date. If you need yours shipped, I am charging a $5 shipping fee. If you do not want to pay by credit card, you can pay when you pick up your masks with a check or exact change.

post_text:
High School Marching Band Camp will be held from Monday, August 24 to Wednesday, August, 26 from 3:30 - 8:30 p.m. Please be sure to bring plenty of water and your dinner. This event is a major factor in how well our band will function this year. Each day of band camp is the same amount of instruction time as an entire week of school, so please do your best to be there! Attached is a google form to be complete for each high school band member. T-shirts will be provided for each student and will be this year’s “uniform”. If you have any questions, please email Band & Choir Director Caleb Crouch at ccrouch@ejps.org.

https://forms.gle/2pVwsgo8byZgpEJq5

post_text:
6th-12th Grade Text Book Collection: Wednesday, 6/24/20 is the last day the EJMHS office will be open for families/students to turn in textbooks/learning materials. Materials can be dropped off between 8:00 a.m.-4:00 pm. Please call 231-536-2259 with any questions or if you need assistance. Please note this does include 6th grade.

These are greatly needed to inventory and prepare for the 2020-2021 school year. Each of these books/learning materials will be utilized in the upcoming school year. Please get these materials turned in to the EJMHS office. Any items not turned in will be added to student fines and will cause immediate material shortages for the incoming classes for the 2020-2021 school year.

Thank you for your support and assistance moving forward.

post_text:
Do you have a child or know of someone who has a child who will be 3 or 4 years old by December 1, 2020?

Begin the registration process for our We Are EJ Preschool Program now! We are EJ Preschool is a Tuition-Free program. Classes are held September through May.

Our preschool balances structured with unstructured activities. In daily free play, children select their own activities from a variety of planned projects. This allows our young learners to explore, improve motor skills, and ready themselves for future schooling.

Our teachers are awesome and use open-ended, hands-on activities that appeal to a wide range of our young learners including visual, kinesthetic, and auditory activities. The Creative Curriculum and The Pre- Kindergarten Literacy Essentials are the curricula used in the classrooms.



Please share this with families you know who may have preschool-aged children! We would love for them to be part of our school family. We are EJ!

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSffyZXLgV6W-ESeFVc3tzo7tmRwNYXlrBr_LInPrEOGPDEYPg/viewform

post_id:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Madison Priest

This fall, Maggie will attend classes at North Central Michigan College. During her time at EJMHS, Maggie participated in tennis, sideline cheer, choir and the Young Americans workshop. Her friends and classmates are what Maggie will miss the most about her days as a Red Devil, and some of her favorite school memories are going to dances with her friends. Mrs. McPherson says,”Maggie has made such growth over her high school years. I appreciate her willingness to try anything and smile as she does it!” Maggie’s advice to the underclassmen is to be patient with yourself, “things will work out just the way they need to.”

Congratulations, Maggie!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Jacob Moses

Jacob has made his mark on EJMHS. As a Red Devil Athlete, he participated in cross country, track and field and golf. Jacob is also a very talented artist. Mr. Schroeder says, “ It has been a great pleasure to have Jacob in the upper art class. He is an amazing artist and will be great in any art related field. Jacob has an amazing understanding of the aesthetics of art and is truly inspirational.” His friends and teachers are what Jacob will miss most about school. His advice to underclassmen is to make good memories, don’t drop out and stay “swagalicious”! Jacob plans to attend college this fall.

EJMHS Congratulates Jacob!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: David Labute

This fall, David will be attending NCMC and then transferring to Northern Michigan University to study athletic training. During his time at EJMHS, David represented the Red Devils in football and baseball and says he’ll miss playing sports with his friends. One of his favorite high school memories was winning the Homecoming game for the first time in many years. His advice for underclassmen? “Participate in the things that you many think are dumb.” Mrs. McPherson says, “I have so enjoyed having David in class -- kind, polite, respectful, funny, hard worker. He is on his way to becoming an amazing adult. “

Congratulations, David!

Some of his best high school memories are hanging out with Mr. Hamilton at lunch. His advice for underclassmen is, “don’t procrastinate”. Mr. Muladore says, “Marshall, thank you for being a team player in class. We wish him all the best!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Caleb Carson

Next year, Caleb plans to attend Rochester University to pursue a degree in secondary education/social studies. During his career at EJMHS, Caleb was actively involved in Student Council, NHS, BPA, Band, and Jazz Band. As a Red Devil Athlete, he was a valued member of both the Cross Country and Track teams. Mr. Peterson says, “I’m very proud of the “growth” Caleb has shown during his middle/high school years. I can’t wait to see what he does in college and beyond.” Neither, can we! We know great things are in Caleb’s future! One of Caleb’s favorite memories was the first day of Senior year when the whole class got to jump in a bouncy house and play corn hole, “I’m really bad at corn hole!” Caleb says he will miss the entire staff and all his fellow Seniors. His advice to underclassmen? “Get out of your head and JUST DO IT!”

Congratulations, Caleb! EJMHS salutes you!

We wish you all the best, Drue!

This fall, Jackson is heading off to Alma College where he will play football and basketball. During his years at EJMHS, Jackson participated in football, baseball, basketball and BPA. Seeing all of his friends is what he will miss the most about his days as a Red Devil. One of Jackson’s best school memories is beating Charlevoix twice in basketball his junior year. His advice to underclassmen is simple: stay on everyone’s good side. Mr Ferguson says, “Jackson, it was awesome to see how you matured as an athlete, and a young man. It is great to see you become a positive leader on the football field and basketball court. Good luck at Alma! (a great school).

We wish him all the best!

post_id:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Logan Argetsinger

During his time at EJMHS, Logan enjoyed participating in band. Some of his best memories from school were exploring the Vietnam Veteran’s Memorial in Washington, D.C. and his band trip to Michigan’s Adventure. Looking back on his Red Devil days, Logan says he’ll miss all the fantastic memories that all the staff created and all the friends/family he made. Mr. Wilson says, “Logan did a nice job in Automotive Technology this year! He is a hard working young man who will do well in the Automotive Field. Logan leaves the underclassmen this advice: Whatever you do, don't argue with your teachers, especially Mrs. McPherson, because she is always right. Also, always do the homework that the teachers give out. This fall, Logan will be attending Kirtland Community College to further his automotive technology knowledge.

Congratulations, Logan!

East Jordan native Kayla Keane recently completed her collegiate running career at the University of Michigan but missed out on her senior outdoor track and field season because of the coronavirus pandemic.

text:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Andrea Lasley

After graduation, Andrea plans to attend North Central Michigan College to pursue a degree in Nursing. During her years at EJMHS, Andrea played volleyball and ran track. At her former school, she was also in RHS cares and Coalition. Her favorite memory actually comes from her time at her “old school” - “it was was the football game that qualified us for the playoffs, we actually had a huge student section and it was so much fun.”
Mr. Nachazel says, “Andrea always brings a smile to my face. She has the ability to light up the whole room,” Andrea will most miss “all of her friends, how close our class was and how close we were to all of our teachers.” Her advice to underclassmen: “Be involved in as much as you can! Dress up for basketball games and football games, cheer on your team, and dress up for spirit week, it is not lame!”

post_id:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Trevor Zeeryp

During his time at EJMHS, Trevor participated in Marching and Jazz Band, as well as NHS. As a Red Devil Athlete, Trevor played basketball. In fact, some of his greatest school memories include playing varsity basketball and, “running onto our amazing gym for two district games with my great coaches and brothers on the team.” Trevor says he’ll miss the EJ community involvement and support. His advice to underclassmen is to get involved with whatever sounds fun and never quit. Mrs. Hardy says, “I always enjoyed having Trevor in my class! He is polite, funny, kind hearted, and hard working. I know he will do great things!” After graduation, Trevor will be joining the Michigan Army National Guard while attending college at Kuyper University for one year before attending the University of Northwestern Ohio to become ASE certified in Automotive Technology.

Congratulations, Trevor!

image:
Mrs. Hewitt's Counseling Corner
May 13 at 6:04 PM ·

I love this analogy!

You are holding a cup of coffee when someone comes along and bumps into you or shakes your arm, making you spill your coffee everywhere.

Why did you spill the coffee?

"Because someone bumped into me!!!"

Wrong answer.

You spilled the coffee because there was coffee in your cup.

Had there been tea in the cup, you would have spilled tea.

*Whatever is inside the cup is what will spill out.*

Therefore, when life comes along and shakes you (which WILL happen), whatever is inside you will come out. It's easy to fake it, until you get rattled.

*So we have to ask ourselves... “what's in my cup?"*

When life gets tough, what spills over?

Joy, gratefulness, peace and humility?

Anger, bitterness, harsh words and reactions?

Life provides the cup, YOU choose how to fill it.

Today let's work towards filling our cups with gratitude, forgiveness, joy, words of affirmation; and kindness, gentleness and love for others.

(Shared from a friend whose cup is full of goodness and inspiration.)

Next year, Augi plans to study early childhood education at North Western Michigan College. During her time at EJMHS, Augi made her mark as a Red Devil Athlete by participating in tennis, color guard, softball and competitive cheer. Augi also was involved in the yearbook committee. Her favorite school memory is growing close to her cheer team members, and Augi says she will miss making memories with all her senior friends. Her advice to underclassmen is, “Don’t give up and make as many memories as you can. Put yourself out there!” Mrs. Walker comments, “Dear sweet Augi! She is the first person to say good morning and always brings a smile to my face. She looks after her classmates and always tries to be a friend to everyone.” Good luck in all your future plans!

Congratulations, Auguste Legato.

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Jayden Weber

Jayden has been an important part of the Red Devil Athletic Department. While at EJMHS, she participated in volleyball, softball and basketball. She was also a member of NHS and BPa. Her three top memories from school are getting her 1000th point in basketball, Camp Daggett in the 5th grade, and the Senior Lock-in. Jayden will miss being with her friends everyday and making memories and feels grateful to be a part of such a close class. Mr. Nachazel says, “Jayden is one of the most thoughtful people I know. She is always thinking of others, and she never hesitates to share a kind word.” She advises underclassmen not to take anything for granted and be thankful, happy and kind. She reminds students that life is too short to complain and be mean, and to remember that every day is a blessing. Jayden plans to attend Grand Valley State University to pursue a nursing degree.

EJMHS congratulates Jayden Weber!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Amber Cetnarowski

Amber participated in many activities during her years at EJMHS. She was a member of NHS, robotics, marching band, and BPA. Amber also represented Red Devil Athletics on the tennis team. Looking back on her days at EJMHS, Amber says she’ll miss her classmates, and her favorite school memory was Ellie’s senior wish. Her advice to the underclassmen is simple: get involved. Mr Essenberg says, “ Amber took the calculus challenge this year, and I was so good to have her in class again.” This fall, Amber will be heading off to Northern Michigan University to study environmental science.

We wish her all the best!

2. If it is pretty and warm outside, go out and play. Ride your bikes, play ball, anything to get some exercise.

Next year, Ellie plans to attend North Central Michigan College where she will study animal science. Ellie was a Red Devil Athlete, participating in softball, volleyball, basketball and sideline cheer. She was also involved in color guard and was crowned Homecoming Queen. Ellie says she will miss making memories with all her friends. One of her best school memories was going down the river with her classmates in 6th grade. Mrs. McPherson says, “Ellie is one of the kindest-hearted students I have ever known. She says, “If you want the truth, be truthful. If you want respect, give respect. If you want kindness, be kind. But remember giving it out doesn’t always guarantee it back and that’s okay.“

EJMHS congratulates Ellie Skrocki!

link:
SENIOR SPOTLIGhT: Alexander Schlueter

Next fall, Alex will be attending Madonna University where he will be studying elementary education and running cross country and track. In fact, those two sports were a big part of his days at EJMHS. One of his favorite school memories was when the CC team won regionals his sophomore year, and “the boys” is Alex’s response to what he’ll miss most about his days as a Red Devil. His advice to underclassmen is, “Do your homework. Just do your homework. Do as much as you can while you're there because you are not gonna know when it ends. “Mr. Nachazel says,” I don't know how to begin to describe Alex. Too many words come to mind. Simply put, he is a great person headed for more greatness. “

We wish him all the best!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Kristin Jones

Kristin plans on attending Baker College of Cadillac next year to pursue her dream of becoming a Veterinary Technician. During her years at EJMHS, Kristin played trumpet for the Red Devil Marching Band. In fact, her favorite school memory was earning a “one” at Band Festival. Mrs. Walker says, “Kristin is such a sweetheart. She is very thoughtful and I appreciate her enthusiastic personality. I will miss her daily "hello" in the hallways. “ Kristin will miss spending time with her friends and fellow seniors, and her advice to underclassmen is, “Don’t slack off; it’ll come back to bite you in the rear!”

Congratulations, Kristin Jones!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Cody King

Next year, Cody will be serving our country as a member of the United States Military. As a Red Devil Athlete, Cody participated in Cross Country. When looking back over the past four years, Cody says it is his family that he will miss the most as he prepares to leave East Jordan. His advice for underclassmen is simple: Don’t hesitate! Mrs. Hardy says, “Cody is the student I go to when I need help: whether it's solving a computer issue, helping organize my cupboards, or building or dismantling a homecoming float, I can always rely on Cody to lend a hand. He will be missed! Thanks for choosing to serve our country!”

Cody King, EJMHS salutes you!

column1: We wish him all the best!"
link:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Parker Cesaro

Athletics have been a big part of Parker’s life. While at EJMHS, Parker participated as a Red Devil athlete in baseball and basketball. He also enjoyed his time coaching elementary boys basketball and helping with the weekend youth basketball program. Parker states, “I will miss going to basketball and baseball practices, and the fun times with all my friends, either traveling to the games on the bus or on the court or the field.” One of his best memories of his school career was the 8th grade trip to Washington, D.C., “ it was a great experience, and I had the best time”. Mr. Essenberg says, “One thing about Parker: he may bring candy to class when he is not supposed to, but he was always willing to share it.” His advice for underclassmen? “Study hard and don’t ever give up. It will be worth it in the end.” In the fall, Parker will be attending North Central Michigan College to study computer hardware design engineering and then transferring to Ferris State University.

We wish him all the best!

link:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Chandler Bartig

While at EJMHS, Chandler made his mark as a Red Devil Athlete, participating in baseball, basketball and football. He was also a member of NHS, and his favorite memory of his school career was Homecoming Week. If he could give advice to underclassmen, he would tell them to, “enjoy every second because it goes fast.” Mr. Hamilton says, “I always appreciated Chandler's humbleness and quiet leadership. He has been a great role model in our school for the younger kids and his peers. Chandler will be missed in our halls and classes - but I look forward to watching him succeed in the years to come”. Next year, Chandler plans to attend NCMC. We wish him all the best in his future endeavors!

EJMHS salutes Chandler Bartig!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Judson Wise
>>>>>>> master

Judson is headed off to Western Michigan University where he plans on majoring in Industrial Engineering. Judd has been a well-rounded student -- excelling in academics, athletics, and community service organization. He participates in football, basketball, track and field, Student Council, National Honor Society, and Business Professionals of America. Mr. Peterson, Judson’s coach says, “Judd is one of the most dependable and dedicated athletes that I've every had the opportunity to coach. He can always be counted on to come through for the team.” Judd says that he will miss his friends, teachers and coaches. His favorite memory of high school will be his 6th Hour Marketing class from his junior year. Judd advises others to participate in all the activities and extra curriculars that you can -- you never know when it will all be over.

Best wishes Judson!

For being selected, these students have each earned a $50 gift card from the local business of their choice. Great job and keep up the good work!

-EJMHS Staff

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Jorden Elmer

Jorden Elmer plans to enter the the world of work after high school. He hopes to be working in a trade field. Mr. Ferguson says, “Jordan, I'm glad you finished strong your senior year. It was great to see you participate in sports and see you in the hallways every day.” During high school, Jorden participated on the Varsity Basketball team. In fact, his favorite memory of high school is playing basketball. He will miss his weightlifting class the most. His advice to underclassmen is for them to figure out what they are best at and then to pursue it.

Congratulations Jorden!

video_thumbnail:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Ben Hardy

Ben plans to attend Aquinas College to pursue a degree in secondary education and compete on the Cross Country and Track teams. During his years at EJMHS Ben ran Cross Country, was on the Track and Field team, was a member of Student Council, NHS and BPA. Ben’s favorite memory was the first time the Cross Country team won the Regional during his sophomore year. Mr. Nachazel says, “I will always remember Ben’s determination. Also, he has been such a huge part of my family’s life. We will miss him.” On the other hand, Ben will miss running with the same group of guys he has ran with for the past 4 years. His advice to underclassmen, “Always make goals and strive towards them, whether in the classroom, on the field or in life.”

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Lillian Ziebarth

Lily plans to attend Oakland University in the fall to pursue a degree in health sciences. While at EJMHS, Lily was a member of NHS and Student Council. She was also an active member of the Red Devil Athletic Department, participating in cross country, tennis, color guard, and sideline and competitive cheer. Lily loved being a part of such an amazing cheer team. One of her favorite school memories was going to States with the cheer team for the first time ever. Lily will miss seeing all of her, “amazing teachers and friends.” Mrs. Hardy says, “I have loved having Lily in my classes! She is kind, talented, hard working and has a heart of gold! I will so miss her sweet smile in the hallway!” Lily’s advice to underclassmen is, “Don’t be afraid to try something new, talk to someone new or experience something new. The best things in high school and life come from taking a chance and stepping out of your comfort zone.”

We wish her all the best!

link:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Kara Feury

Next year Kara plans to attend Central Michigan University to pursue a degree in secondary education with an emphasis on English and ESL. She also hopes to play in the Chippewa Marching Band. While at EJMHS, Kara was involved in concert, marching, and jazz bands. She was also in robotics, honors band and quiz bowl. As a Red Devil athlete she was on the cross country and track & field teams. Mrs. Walker had this to say about Kara, “As I have gotten to know Kara I appreciate how much she has grown through her many challenges. I wish her the best as she moves on to CMU and will miss her witty puns and beautiful smile!” Kara says that she will miss the never ending support that comes with her classmates and tight knit community. Her favorite senior memories were float building and painting the senior parking spots. Her advice to others is to appreciate everything, always say “yes” and keep a kind heart, even when it’s difficult to do so.

EJMHS congratulates Kara!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Emily Lamb

This fall, Emily plans to attend North Central Michigan College. As a Red Devil Athlete, Emily participated in Track and Field, Volleyball and Cheerleading. Mr. Hamilton says, “I enjoyed having Emily in Photojournalism this year. She is an incredible young lady filled with talent and ability. She will be missed, but I look forward to watching and hearing about her many successes in the future! “ What Emily will miss most about her time at EJMHS is seeing all her friends. We wish you all the best, Emily!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Jack Cross

Jack plans on attending a 2 or 4 year college next year. During his years at EJMHS, Jack played both football and basketball all four years. His favorite memory from his time at EJMHS is “all of it” and if you know Jack- he finds a way to enjoy every part of everyday. Mr. Fleshman says, “Jack never ceases to amaze me with his academic talents. Always naturally curious, Jack is full of questions but most importantly, he is determined to find answers.” Jack will miss the amazing staff at EJMHS (especially Nacho). His advice to underclassmen: “DO YOUR HOMEWORK.”

>>>>>>> master

Next year Molly will attend Northwood University where she plans to study accounting. She will also be running on their cross country and track teams. While at EJMHS, Molly was a member of the Student Council, NHS, and Business Professionals of America. She was also the school’s blood drive coordinator. As a Red Devil athlete, she participated in cross country, basketball, softball, and track & field. Mr. Peterson had this to say about Molly, “Despite writing on my table with an eraser as a middle schooler and finally admitting to it as a senior, I have the utmost respect for Molly’s integrity, hard work and dedication. She’s going to do great in college.” Molly’s favorite memory at EJMHS was the BPA State Leadership Conference in 2019. Molly said that she will miss her friends and how close knit they all are the most. Her advice to others is to not take anything for granted, you never know when it will be your last chance.

EJMHS congratulates, Molly Kitson!

post_id:
SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Hunter Adams

Next year, Hunter plans to attend Bethel University in Indiana to study mechanical engineering. While at EJMHS, Hunter was a member of NHS, Student Council and the Senior planning committee and was very active in his church. As a Red Devil Athlete he participated in Football and Track. Mrs. Hardy said, “In the classroom and out, Hunter is an amazing person. He never hesitates to help or encourage others. He is kind and hardworking and will definitely be missed!” Hunter is a hard working young man who will succeed in whatever he chooses to do. Hunter said he will miss his friends and the friendly atmosphere at EJMHS. His favorite memory of school was the senior lock-in. His advice for others is to not take these years for granted because they will be done before you know it. So, make as many memories as you can.

Congratulations, Hunter Adams!

SENIOR SPOTLIGHT: Lauren Peterson

Lauren plans to attend NCMC to pursue a degree in business with an emphasis on accounting. While at EJMHS, Lauren was a member of NHS and Student Council. She also participated in Red Devils’ Athletics in Volleyball, Basketball, and Softball every year. Mrs. McPherson says “Lauren is one of those “go to it” students you can always count on to step up and get something done. I appreciate her work ethic!” Lauren says that she will miss the friendly environment at school and the feeling of family that came along with it. Her favorite memory was going to Camp Willy and all of the fun she had there with her friends and teachers. Lauren's advice to the underclassmen is to never take anything for granted. You never know when something could be gone forever.

EJMHS congratulates you, Lauren Peterson!

post_text: Happy Friday Red Devils! We hope that your first week of remote learning is going well. In an effort to provide support information for our students, parent and community.....we have been collecting items and developing areas on our website to make it easier to access. Please go to www.ejps.org and you will notice two "banners" on our front page. Under the "COVID-19" banner, you will find updates from the Governor and Local Health agencies along with supports and ideas for our students and families during this time. School information can be found by clicking the "Remote Learning Support" banner. Here you will find information on our lunch program, technology supports, counselor/social worker contacts and remote classroom supports. We hope these resources are helpful as we all move forward. Thanks for your support during these trying times.

East Jordan Career Technical Education
April 7 at 9:34 PM ·

East Jordan Middle High School senior, Trevor Zeeryp has been selected by the CTE faculty as the March 2020 Career & Technical Education Student of the Month. Trevor is an automotive technology student who would like to pursue a career as an ASE Certified Automotive Technician. He enjoys being outdoors, hunting, and camping. He has been a member of the National Honor Society, basketball team, football team, golf team, the high school marching band and Jazz band. He is the son of Kimberly and Nathan Zeeryp.

post_text:
Dear East Jordan Families:
As part of our distance learning plan, teachers will be contacting you this week from telephone numbers which you may not recognize. They will be reaching out in order to check in and gain valuable information as we work to finalize our learning plan for the remainder of the school year.
Please consider answering calls from these unknown numbers so our teachers can communicate with you and your children.
We have also added a new "banner" on our website that will contain updated information on the COVID-19 pandemic and critical information for families as we move through this process together.

post_text: Over the past two days, the news that we have dreaded has finally become a reality. Yesterday, Governor Whitmer suspended face to face instruction for the remainder of the school year and today, MHSAA canceled the remainder of the winter and spring sports season. Staff here in East Jordan have been working diligently to plan for food service, social/emotional support and to develop our distance learning plan. Next week, we finalize our distance learning plan as well as develop food service preparations and social/emotional supports moving forward. We would like to thank you for your patience and cooperation during this transition. The administrators, teaching staff, and technology teams have been working on plans to continue educating our children. School is not over! It's just going to look a bit different for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year. Information will be sent to parents via email by the end of next week, April 10th, that will outline our plan for the education of our students. #ejproud

Here is a fun science project brought to you by Raven Hill Discovery Center!

Raven Hill Discovery Center
March 21 at 3:25 PM ·

The simplest things can keep a kid’s mind active! Try dropping a single drop food coloring in a glass of water. How long does it take to diffuse completely and have all the water blue? What happens, if you try different water temperatures or put two different colors in at once or...........Let your kids ask the questions and see, if together, you can find the answers by experimenting. Stay tuned for other ideas informal learning opportunities from Raven Hill. Comments welcome.

post_text: Good morning East Jordan Red Devils! Please note that we are OPEN today, Friday March 13th, and will operate as normal. In accordance with the Governor's mandate from late last evening, we will be closing beginning Monday, March 16th and will be planning to reopen Tuesday, April 7th following our regularly scheduled spring break. ALL school related activities will be cancelled/postponed during this time. Students should bring all belongings and school materials home at the end of the day today. More communication will be forthcoming as this rapidly evolving situation changes. We thank you for your understanding!

East Jordan Middle High School senior, Lillii Armstrong, has been selected by the CTE faculty as the February 2020 Career & Technical Education Student of the Month. Her CTE courses include welding, BAMO, and autos. She plans to pursue a career in welding and fabrication in the future. Lillii enjoys powerlifting, juggling, working with livestock, and welding. She is a four-time state champion powerlifter. She has also been a top qualifier at Nationals and placed 3rd in the Worlds Powerlifting competition. She will continue to compete at elite powerlifting competitions throughout the year. Lillii is the daughter of Patsy Armstrong.

Congratulations to our award winners as well. We at EJPS are blessed to have so many that do so much for our students.

The Health Department of Northwest Michigan was the recipient of our "Champion For Children Award".

Thomas Reid Jr was the recipient of the "Red Devil Award".

The "We Are EJ Award" was presented to Ruthann Sheridan, in memory of the late Tom Sheridan.

post_text:
Job Posting - Coaching Position
East Jordan Public Schools is seeking to fill the girls varsity volleyball position for next fall.
Candidates must show competency in the specific coaching area sought, have the ability to plan, develop and implement a quality program. Candidates must display basic knowledge of physical conditioning and first aid as well as demonstrate a strong commitment to positive sportsmanship for themselves and their students.
Interested candidates should file a letter of interest and current resume, including references with: Phyllis Olszewski, Athletic Director, East Jordan Public Schools, PO Box 399, East Jordan, MI 49727 or by email to polszewski@ejps.org.
Application Deadline: April 1, 2020.
https://www.ejps.org/

shared_text:
Sixth grade students practice driving ATVs through an obstacle course during STEAM class with Mr. Ziebarth. This STEAM lesson focuses on physical science concepts related to robotics, in a hands-on, team atmosphere learning environment.

Prior to starting the obstacle course, Mya Arnold and teammate, Caleb Jakobowski, check the ATV to ensure that the on-board camera is communicating with the iPad. The camera will project the image of the course and its obstacles to the iPad. It's the driver's job to watch the iPad screen and maneuver the vehicle using the wireless hand-held remote controller. While watching the iPad screen, the driver sees the road from the perspective of being behind the wheel of the ATV. Other team members are Kendra Behrendt and Harry Hague.These 6th grade students were up for the challenge. Great job drivers! #ejproud #weareej

The annual EJHS theater trip this year is to Grand Rapids on March 12th to see Charlie and the Chocolate Factory. Sign up to reserve your spot. Seniors will have priority registration starting at 7:30am on Thursday Feb 13th in the art room. 9th 10th and 11th graders well be able to sign up Tuesday Feb 18th starting at 7:30 in the art room. Spots are limited. All tickets sold are on a first-come first-serve basis. Cost for the ticket is $25. Students will also need to pay for dinner.

https://youtu.be/tt0TdBU3afU

Students 3rd-12th grade will participate in performance workshops on March 8-10 at the Middle/High School and perform with the Young Americans on Tuesday, March 10. Thanks to a local donor, the cost for EJPS students is only $19!
Visit: https://reg.youngamericans.org/Registration/Event/224F95E7363942C992E24E86CF093959 to register today.

post_text: All high school students are welcome to participate in the next SAFE after hours event being held at the Charlevoix Cinema on Friday, February 14.
